I0602 05:47:15.812530 1152912 input_loop.go:34] HandleUserInput called with text: "1 temporary 2 Must preserve (or compilation fails):\n    - remappings — critical. The virtual sources use import paths like @openzeppelin/contracts/.... Without the remappings, those imports won't resolve and you get the exact Unknown file class of error.\n    Whatever materialization route you take, the remappings have to be carried over (into foundry.toml, or via --solc-remaps, or by writing the sources at paths that satisfy the imports).\n    - The exact source tree — every entry in sources must be written to disk at its key path, because imports are path-relative.\n\n    Should preserve (correctness, occasionally compilation):\n    - evmVersion — matters if the contract uses opcodes gated by EVM version (e.g. PUSH0 on Shanghai+, or older targets like istanbul). Mismatches can change codegen or, rarely, fail. For static \n    analysis it's low-risk, but for the EVM verifier later it matters more (deployed-bytecode fidelity), so carry it through.\n    - The compiler version — not in settings but in metadata.json (CompilerVersion). You already handle this in label.py via solc-select; use the same per-contract version here.\n\n    Can usually ignore for Slither:\n    - optimizer / runs — these affect bytecode, not the AST/IR Slither analyzes. crytic-compile typically overrides outputSelection anyway to get the AST it needs. Optimizer settings don't change\n    detector results in any way that matters for weak labels. (You would want them if you were reproducing exact bytecode — e.g. matching the on-chain BytecodeHash — but labeling doesn't need that.)\n    - outputSelection — ignore/override; crytic-compile sets its own.\n    - libraries — only relevant if the contract has unlinked libraries and you're producing deployable bytecode; harmless to pass through but not needed for AST-level analysis.\n\n    The important nuance: the cleanest materialization path is often to not hand the raw standard-JSON to crytic at all, but instead write the sources to a temp tree and let Foundry compile (it was the\n    most robust route noted in the architecture). If you go that way, you translate the JSON settings into foundry.toml: remappings, evm_version, solc_version, and optionally optimizer/optimizer_runs.\n    So the answer becomes \"yes, you re-express the relevant settings, but in Foundry's config form.\"\n\n    So: remappings yes, evmVersion yes (cheap insurance, and needed for the verifier), compiler version yes (from metadata), optimizer/outputSelection/libraries no for labeling."
